Intro¶

You have been using the numpy package a lot, haven't you? Let's see the people that have been contributing to this package. Using Github API, let's request the list of contributors of the numpy package. Let's use all the default parameters for now. From the documentation, we can see that we make all our requests to api.github.com. But how to request the contributors specifically? Let's go back to the documentation: list contributors (please read it - it is just like three lines). Read it? Really? Are you sure? Ok, let's move on.

So the API is saying that, to request the contributors we make a GET request GET /repos/:owner/:repo/contributors. The : is placeholder for the specific values that you want. In the case of numpy, :owner = numpy and :repo=numpy. Let's make our request.

In [2]:
domain = "https://api.github.com" # The domain name
request_contributors = "/repos/numpy/numpy/contributors" # our request

response = requests.get(domain + request_contributors)

print("Status: {} - {}".format(response.status_code, response.reason))

Status: 200 - OK

Good, it seems that our request was successful. Let's check it out the data we got.

In [3]:

Look how cool is that, the response object already has a built-in JSON decoder. Above we printed just the first contributor to be easier to read. But let's save this JSON response into a variable, and check out how many contributiors we have.

In [4]:
data = response.json()
print("Number of contributors:", len(data))

Number of contributors: 30

Hmmm, weird! Something is not right here. Is it possible that a open-source project as big as numpy has only 30 contributors? Let's investigate this. In the repository's page we can see that the number of contributors is over 700!

So, what is going on here? Why didn't the API returned all the contributors? Well, Github uses Pagination (again, please read this - it is very short). So, basically, by default, Github uses pagination with 30 elements per page. Oh, now things start make sense. Also, there should be pagination information in the response's headers, more precisely, in the link field, let's check it out.

In [5]:
response.headers['link']
Out[5]:
'<https://api.github.com/repositories/908607/contributors?page=2>; rel="next", <https://api.github.com/repositories/908607/contributors?page=14>; rel="last"'

So, in the headers of the response, the API provides the hyperlink to the next page of results. Cool!

But we also saw in Pagination that we can change this default. In order to do that, all we need to do is to pass parameters to the server. This can be done by including ?param1=value after your request. For example, we could use:

  1. domain: https://api.github.com
  2. request: /repos/numpy/numpy/contributors
  3. parameter: ?per_page=100

which results in https://api.github.com/repos/numpy/numpy/contributors?per_page=100 (go ahead, click it!).

Although you can just build the url and pass it to requests.get, requests makes it easier for you to deal with parameters. Let's change the number of parameter in our request now using requests.

In [6]:
# This is what we defined before
domain = "https://api.github.com" # The domain name
request_contributors = "/repos/numpy/numpy/contributors" # our request

# Now, we can define the set of parameter as a dictionary 
params = {"per_page": 100}

# Now we call requests
response2 = requests.get(domain + request_contributors, params)

print("Status: {} - {}".format(response2.status_code, response2.reason))

Status: 200 - OK

Cool, the request was successful. Let's check our new data now.

In [7]:
data = response2.json()
len(data)
Out[7]:
100

It worked, now we have 100 contributors in the first page! But how did requests handle this for us? No mistery. Let's check the url used by requests.

In [8]:
response2.url
Out[8]:
'https://api.github.com/repos/numpy/numpy/contributors?per_page=100'

Exactly the one we built above. All requests did was to merge everything together for us, so our code can be more organized. But still, pretty cool!

Ok, now you know how to make a request to Github and also how to pass parametes with your request. One last thing before you jump to your exercises. Here we only worked with the GET request. But you will frequently need to use other verbs, such as

  1. PUT - usually used to change things
  2. POST - usually used to create things
  3. DELETE - usually used to remove things

Also, different APIs will work differently. So, you'll always need to consult the documentation. In fact, Github has a version 4 API that is not a REST API, but a GraphQL API, which seems to be increasing in popularity.

Exercise 1¶

In this exercise we are going to build a very simple python wrapper for the Alpha Vantage API. It is a free API to collect stock market data, however it still requires authentication. So, get your free api key today! Just fill in the form, and get your key (careful, the key is generated in the same webpage, just below the "Get free api key" button). Save this key, it is kind of important for this exercise. Cool! We are set.

Just one important note, here we are dealing with a real API, not just a Toy one. They are kind enough to give us free access to their API, and the only thing they ask is for you to "make API requests sparingly (up to 5 API requests per minute and 500 requests per day) to achieve the best server-side performance". So, let's try to follow this request.

A useful way to work with api keys is to set enviromment variables with the value of the key. Then you can just retrieve them using python os package. To create new environment variables:

  • on windows: open Powershell and type: [Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable('variable_name', 'variable_value', 'User'), where variable_name is the name for your variable (e.g., ALPHA_API), variable_value is your api key, and Users is specyfing the scope of the variable (e.g., if you want your variable available to all the users you would use Machine instead. But here we don't want that). Note that the variable will be available only in the next sessions.

  • on Mac/Linux: export variable_name=variable_value. This will make the variable available only in the current session. As far as I know, to add a variable persistently in linux/Mac you need to store in the .bash_profile (but you might want to check that out).

  • To access an environment variable in a python session you run:

          import os
      os.environ['variable_name']

Although there are some wrappers already defined for Alpha Vantage API, this is for you to learn. In the future, if you find a useful API that has no wrapper in either R or Python, you could make your own wrapper, create a package and publish it. The community would be grateful.

The idea of a wrapper is to create a set of functions to handle the requests for us, so it is easier to work with the API in a specific language.

Now, take a look at the API documentation.

def Get_TimeSeries(stock, period):
    """
    A wrapper function to obtain the the time series of a the desired stock from the Alpha Vantage API.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    stock: the desired stock symbol (e.g., "GOOG", "AMD", "FB", "INTC").
    period: "daily", "weekly", "monthly"
    
    Returns:
    --------
    A pandas dataframe with the columns `open`, `high`, `low`, and `close`.
    """
    
    # Process here the parameter `period`
    # which affects the function parameter in the API
    
    # TODO
    if period.upper() == 'DAILY':
        func = 'TIME_SERIES_DAILY'
    elif period.upper() == 'WEEKLY':
        func = 'TIME_SERIES_WEEKLY'
    elif period.upper() == 'MONTHLY':
        func = 'TIME_SERIES_MONTHLY'
    else:
        print('You have input an invalid time period. Input "daily", "weekly", or "monthly"')

    
    
    
    # Now let's create a dictionary to hold the parameters of 
    # our request.
    
    # TODO
    params = {}
    params['function'] = func
    params['symbol'] = stock.upper()
    params['apikey'] = os.environ['ALPHA_API']
    params['outputsize'] = 'full'

    # Requesting the data
    
    # TODO
    url = "https://www.alphavantage.co/query"
    time_data = requests.get(url, params)
    
    
    
    # Check if the request was successful, if not raise an
    # exception
    try:
        print("Status: {} - {}".format(time_data.status_code, time_data.reason))
        if time_data.status_code != 200:
            raise ValueError
    except ValueError:
        print("The request was not successful")
        
    
    
    # Create the pandas dataframe (see: pd.read_json() )
    
    # TODO
    data_df = pd.read_json(time_data.text)

    # Wrangle the data to create columns of high, low, and close.
    if period.upper() == 'DAILY':
        selected_time = data_df.columns[1].split()[2]
        time_period = 'Time Series ' + selected_time
        time_select = data_df[time_period][5:]
    else:
        selected_time = data_df.columns[1].split()[0]
        time_period = selected_time + ' Time Series'
        time_select = data_df[time_period][4:]
    
        
    time_df = pd.DataFrame(time_select)
    time_expanded = time_df[time_period].apply(pd.Series)
    time_expanded = time_expanded.iloc[:, 1:4]
    time_expanded = time_expanded.rename(columns= {'2. high': 'High', '3. low': 'Low', '4. close': 'Close'})
    time_expanded.index = pd.to_datetime(time_expanded.index, format="%Y/%m/%d")
    time_expanded = time_expanded.apply(pd.to_numeric)
    return time_expanded, stock, period

# Run the function
data = Get_TimeSeries('BB', 'daily')
data_df = data[0]
stock = data[1]
period = data[2]
period = period[0].upper() + period[1:]
# plot the figure
plt.figure()
#data_df.plot(ylabel= "Price ($)", xlabel= "Date", title= f"{} Stock Price Information")
plt.figure()
data_df.plot(ylabel= "Price ($)", xlabel= "Date", title= f"{stock} Stock Price {period} Time-Series Information")

def Get_TimeSeries_FX(from_currency, to_currency, period):
    """
    A wrapper function to obtain the the time series of the foreign exchange rate between two currencies from the Alpha Vantage API.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    from_currency: Three letter symbol of currency we are exchanging from (e.g. "USD", "CAD").
    to_currency: Three letter symbol of currency we are exchanging to (e.g. "USD", "CAD").
    period: "daily", "weekly", "monthly"
    
    Returns:
    --------
    A pandas dataframe with the columns `open`, `high`, `low`, and `close`.
    """
    # Process parameters
    if period.upper() == 'DAILY':
        func = 'FX_DAILY'
    elif period.upper() == 'WEEKLY':
        func = 'FX_WEEKLY'
    elif period.upper() == 'MONTHLY':
        func = 'FX_MONTHLY'
    else:
        print('You have input an invalid time period. Input "daily", "weekly", or "monthly"')

    currency_df = pd.read_csv('physical_currency_list.csv')
    currency_codes = list(currency_df['currency code'])

    from_currency_var = from_currency.upper()
    if from_currency not in currency_codes:
        print("Invalid three letter currency code for from_country. Choose one from the following dataframe and run the function again:")


    to_currency_var = to_currency.upper()
    if to_currency not in currency_codes:
        print("Invalid three letter currency code for to_country. Choose one from the following dataframe and run the function again:")

    # Store parameters

    params = {}
    params['function'] = func
    params['from_symbol'] = from_currency_var
    params['to_symbol'] = to_currency_var
    params['apikey'] = os.environ['ALPHA_API']
    params['outputsize'] = 'full'

    # Requesting the data

    url = "https://www.alphavantage.co/query"
    time_data = requests.get(url, params)

      # Check if the request was successful, if not raise an
    # exception
    try:
        print("Status: {} - {}".format(time_data.status_code, time_data.reason))
        if time_data.status_code != 200:
            raise ValueError
    except ValueError:
        print("The request was not successful")

    # Create Dataframe

    data_df = pd.read_json(time_data.text)

    # Wrangle the data to create columns of high, low, and close.
    selected_time = data_df.columns[1].split()[3]
    time_period = 'Time Series FX ' + selected_time

    if period.upper() == 'DAILY':
        time_select = data_df[time_period][6:]
    else:
        time_select = data_df[time_period][5:]
    
        
    time_df = pd.DataFrame(time_select)
    time_expanded = time_df[time_period].apply(pd.Series)
    time_expanded = time_expanded.iloc[:, 1:4]
    time_expanded = time_expanded.rename(columns= {'2. high': 'High', '3. low': 'Low', '4. close': 'Close'})
    time_expanded.index = pd.to_datetime(time_expanded.index, format="%Y/%m/%d")
    time_expanded = time_expanded.apply(pd.to_numeric)
    return time_expanded, from_currency_var, to_currency_var, period

def Get_Tech_Ind(indicator, stock, interval, time_period, series_type):
    """
    A wrapper function to obtain the the time series of a selected technical indicator of the desired stock from the Alpha Vantage API.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    indicator (str): The desired technical indicator abreviation to retrieve (e.g. "SMA", "EMA")
    stock (str): the desired stock symbol (e.g., "GOOG", "AMD", "FB", "INTC").
    interval (str): Time interval between two consecutive data points in the time series. Supported intervals are "1min", "5min", "15min", "30min", "60min", "daily", "weekly", "monthly". 
    time_period (int): Number of data points used to calculate the indicator. Positive integers accepted (e.g. 60, 200)
    series_type (str): Desired price type in the time series. Supported price types: "close", "open", "high", "low".

    
    Returns:
    --------
    A pandas dataframe with the selected time series as index and the selected series_type as the column. 
    """
    # assign parameters

    params = {}
    params['function'] = indicator.upper()
    params['symbol'] = stock.upper()
    params['interval'] = interval.lower()
    params['time_period'] = time_period
    params['series_type'] = series_type.lower()
    params['apikey'] = os.environ['ALPHA_API']
    params['outputsize'] = 'full'

    # Requesting the data
    
    url = "https://www.alphavantage.co/query"
    time_data = requests.get(url, params)

    # Check if the request was successful, if not raise an exception
    try:
        print("Status: {} - {}".format(time_data.status_code, time_data.reason))
        if time_data.status_code != 200:
            raise ValueError
    except ValueError:
        print("The request was not successful")

    data_df = pd.read_json(time_data.text)

    # Wrangle the data to creat a single column indexed by date.
    selected_ind = data_df.columns[1].split()[2]
    col_name = 'Technical Analysis: ' + selected_ind
    ind_select = data_df[col_name][7:]
    ind_df = pd.DataFrame(ind_select)
    ind_expanded = ind_df[col_name].apply(pd.Series)
    ind_expanded.index = pd.to_datetime(ind_expanded.index, format="%Y/%m/%d")
    ind_expanded = ind_expanded.apply(pd.to_numeric)
    return ind_expanded, stock
    



# Run the function and return the dataframe.
data = Get_Tech_Ind(indicator="SMA", stock="IBM", interval="monthly", time_period="30", series_type="high")
indicator_df = data[0]
stock = data[1].upper()

# Plot the data. 
plt.figure()
indicator_df.plot(ylabel= "Technical Indicator Value", xlabel= "Date", title= f"{stock} Stock Technical Indicator Time-Series")

Final Comments¶

This lab is just to give you a taste of what you can do with APIs.There are tons of APIs out in the wild. Take a look at this Github page for example. Now, APIs are not just for connecting to data sources. For example, there's a Google Calendar API for programmatically interacting with Google Calendar, an eBay API for interacting with eBay, etc. The Slack API allows a user to programmatically join channels. The GitHub API also isn't just for grabbing data; you can use it to programmatically open issues, make commits, etc. This is actually how we use it here in MDS. Imagine if we had to create repositories for each student manually?

Always take a look at the documentation of the API you are going to use and have fun!
